Explanation:

The MedianFinder class maintains two lists, left_numbers and right_numbers, to store the numbers added. When finding the median, we first check if either list has a length greater than or equal to the other. If so, the median is the value at index len(sorted_numbers//2. If both lists have the same length, the median is the average of the two middle values.

The solution uses a set to remove duplicates from the concatenated lists before sorting, which improves efficiency by reducing the time complexity from O(n^2) to O(n). The space complexity is O(n) due to storing the numbers in two lists. The energy implications are low as the solution only involves adding and removing elements from memory, which has low energy consumption.

